    {
        "function": {
            "name": "activate_browser_interaction_tools",
            "description": "Call this tool when you need access to a new category of tools. The category of tools is described as follows:\n\nThis group of tools is designed for interacting with web pages programmatically using the Playwright framework. The tools allow users to perform a variety of actions such as clicking on elements, navigating between pages, handling dialogs, and simulating keyboard input. These functionalities are essential for automating web testing, scraping data, or simulating user interactions in a browser environment.\n\nUsers can navigate to specific URLs, go back to previous pages, and resize the browser window to test responsive designs. The ability to hover over elements and select options from dropdowns enhances the automation capabilities, making it easier to interact with dynamic web content.\n\nAdditionally, the tools enable users to run custom Playwright code snippets, providing flexibility for advanced automation scenarios. This group is particularly useful for developers and testers who need to create automated scripts for web applications, ensuring that all interactive elements function as expected.\n\nBy combining these tools, users can create comprehensive test scripts that mimic real user behavior, allowing for thorough testing of web applications. The integration of these functionalities streamlines the process of web automation, making it efficient and effective.\n\nOverall, this group serves as a foundational set of tools for anyone looking to automate interactions with web pages, whether for testing, data extraction, or other purposes.\n\nBe sure to call this tool if you need a capability related to the above."
        },
        "type": "function"
    },
    {
        "function": {
            "name": "activate_form_and_file_management_tools",
            "description": "Call this tool when you need access to a new category of tools. The category of tools is described as follows:\n\nThis group focuses on managing forms and file uploads within web applications using Playwright. The tools provided allow users to fill out multiple form fields efficiently, which is crucial for automating user input in testing scenarios or data entry tasks. This capability ensures that all necessary information can be inputted quickly and accurately, simulating real user interactions with forms.\n\nIn addition to form filling, the tools also facilitate the uploading of one or multiple files. This is particularly useful for applications that require users to submit documents, images, or other files as part of their workflow. The ability to automate file uploads can significantly enhance testing processes, ensuring that file handling features work correctly under various conditions.\n\nTogether, these tools can be used to create comprehensive automated test scripts that cover both form submissions and file uploads, allowing for thorough validation of web application functionalities. This is especially important for applications that rely heavily on user-generated content or require extensive data entry.\n\nBy leveraging these tools, developers and testers can ensure that their applications handle forms and file uploads seamlessly, improving the overall user experience. This group is essential for anyone involved in web development or testing, as it addresses common tasks that are often time-consuming when performed manually.\n\nOverall, this group provides essential capabilities for managing user input and file submissions, making it a vital component of automated web testing and data management.\n\nBe sure to call this tool if you need a capability related to the above."
        },
        "type": "function"
    },
    {
        "function": {
            "name": "activate_page_capture_tools",
            "description": "Call this tool when you need access to a new category of tools. The category of tools is described as follows:\n\nThis group of tools is dedicated to capturing visual representations of web pages, offering both screenshot and accessibility snapshot functionalities. The tools allow users to take screenshots of the current page, which can be useful for documentation, reporting, or visual testing purposes. Screenshots provide a static image of the page at a specific moment, helping to verify the appearance and layout of web applications.\n\nIn addition to standard screenshots, the accessibility snapshot tool captures a more detailed representation of the page, focusing on accessibility features. This is particularly beneficial for developers and testers who need to ensure that their web applications are compliant with accessibility standards and provide a good user experience for all users, including those with disabilities.\n\nThese tools can be used together to create a comprehensive visual testing strategy. For instance, a user might take a screenshot before and after making changes to a web page to visually confirm that the changes have been applied correctly. Similarly, accessibility snapshots can be compared against design specifications to ensure that all elements are accessible.\n\nBy integrating these tools into their testing workflows, developers can enhance their ability to identify visual discrepancies and accessibility issues, leading to higher quality web applications. This group is particularly useful for quality assurance teams and developers focused on user experience and compliance.\n\nOverall, this group provides essential capabilities for capturing and analyzing the visual aspects of web pages, making it a critical component of web development and testing processes.\n\nBe sure to call this tool if you need a capability related to the above."
        },
        "type": "function"
    },
